Development Summary (Phase 1 – Recon Pipeline)

PEST v1 was designed and implemented as a Kali-native reconnaissance automation framework focused on structured enumeration and report generation.

Objectives Completed

  Established modular project architecture separating execution, parsing, findings normalization, and reporting layers.
  Implemented CLI-driven entry point (pest.py) for controlled workflow execution.

  Developed a preflight validation module to:
  Verify Nmap availability
  Validate sudo execution
  Create target-scoped output directories
  Integrated automated Nmap reconnaissance module using:
      SYN scanning (-sS)
      Service detection (-sV)
      Default script execution (-sC)
      XML + text artifact generation

Built XML parsing engine using xml.etree.ElementTree to extract open port and service data.
Created structured JSON findings model for normalized attack surface representation.
Implemented markdown-based reporting engine to generate human-readable recon summaries.

Artifacts Generated Per Target

  nmap.xml – Structured scan output
  nmap.txt – Human-readable scan results
  findings.json – Normalized attack surface data model
  report.md – Report-ready recon summary

Engineering Challenges Resolved

Corrected Linux ownership and permission conflicts caused by initial root directory creation.
Refactored project into user-space directory for proper development workflow.
Diagnosed VMware networking segmentation after encountering “0 hosts up” condition during scanning.
Implemented disciplined environment setup and artifact isolation practices.

Current State:

PEST v1 successfully performs:
Automated reconnaissance
Structured service extraction
JSON findings generation
Markdown report output

**The framework is operational within authorized lab environments.**

